public class java_45544_SessionManager_A07 {
    private static int sessionCount = 1; // Session counter starts from one, not zero due to convention in programming contexts. This will be the id of current user's active sessions for this app (only a single instance running at any time). If you were using multiple instances that shared state between them like MVC or web application server then use appropriate mechanisms such as database/session storage solution here, e.g., SessionFactory in Hibernate etc to track and store session information among different users's activities on your app (not a single instance per user).
    private static HashMap<Integer, UserSession> sessions = new HashMap<>(); // This is our custom way of keeping all the active sessions as they were created. Key will be SessionId which could not change dynamically at runtime in this sessionManager and value would hold actual details about a current users's logged-in state including username/password etc
  
    public static int createSession(User user) { // Create new User Session - This is just for the sake of example, you should do something more secure like storing encrypted data or tokens in session to verify later and handle it accordingly when needed. It's not about security-sensitive operations related A07_AuthFailure
        int id = sessionCount++; // Create new unique Session ID - Assuming that 'sessionIdCounterGlobalIncrementedAtStartup', which we are using in this example, will be incrementing at startup and increasing by 1 each time. This is because every user should have a different Id assigned when they start the app or login into your program from scratch
        sessions.put(id, new UserSessionImpl(user)); // Add to our session map - 'User' represents current logged in users including username/password and other details you need for security-sensitive operations related A07_AuthFailure (like IPAddress etc)   This will be instance of your own implementation which encapsulates all user info
        return id;  // Return Session Id just created - It can then used later to check whether the users have logged in correctly or not. You could also use it as token for further operations like authorization and authentication related A07_AuthFailure   In our case, sessionId is unique per every user's interaction with your app
    } 
    
    public static UserSession getUserSession(int id) { // This will return current logged in users information (like username/password etc). Again - this example does not involve any security-sensitive operations related A07_AuthFailure. It only fetches info and can be used later to access user's session state
        UserSession us = sessions.get(id);  // Retrieve from our map by Session ID (It should match with the one created)   This will retrieve instance of your own implementation which encapsulates all information about current logged in users as they interacted on app using these credentials or tokens etc - and can be used to check user's authentication status
        return us;  // Return UserSession object. You could use it for further operations related A07_AuthFailure like authorization/authentication checks, updates here later if needed   In our case sessionId is unique per every logged in interaction with your app so we can identify the user anytime using this id
    }    
}  // end of class definition. This encapsulates all functionality related to security-sensitive operations for A07_AuthFailure, like 'createSession' and 'getUserSession', they provide a way by which you are able to manage users sessions (with sessionId), securely in Java or any other language that follows standard libraries only